CHAPTER II. The Pool of Tears\
\
\'91Curiouser and curiouser!\'92 cried Alice (she was so much surprised, that\
for the moment she quite forgot how to speak good English); \'91now I\'92m\
opening out like the largest telescope that ever was! Good-bye, feet!\'92\
(for when she looked down at her feet, they seemed to be almost out of\
sight, they were getting so far off). \'91Oh, my poor little feet, I wonder\
who will put on your shoes and stockings for you now, dears? I\'92m sure\
_I_ shan\'92t be able! I shall be a great deal too far off to trouble\
myself about you: you must manage the best way you can;--but I must be\
kind to them,\'92 thought Alice, \'91or perhaps they won\'92t walk the way I want\
to go! Let me see: I\'92ll give them a new pair of boots every Christmas.\'92\
\
And she went on planning to herself how she would manage it. \'91They must\
go by the carrier,\'92 she thought; \'91and how funny it\'92ll seem, sending\
presents to one\'92s own feet! And how odd the directions will look!\
\
     ALICE\'92S RIGHT FOOT, ESQ.\
       HEARTHRUG,\
         NEAR THE FENDER,\
           (WITH ALICE\'92S LOVE).\
\
Oh dear, what nonsense I\'92m talking!\'92\
\
Just then her head struck against the roof of the hall: in fact she was\
now more than nine feet high, and she at once took up the little golden\
key and hurried off to the garden door.\
\
Poor Alice! It was as much as she could do, lying down on one side, to\
look through into the garden with one eye; but to get through was more\
hopeless than ever: she sat down and began to cry again.\
\
\'91You ought to be ashamed of yourself,\'92 said Alice, \'91a great girl like\
you,\'92 (she might well say this), \'91to go on crying in this way! Stop this\
moment, I tell you!\'92 But she went on all the same, shedding gallons of\
tears, until there was a large pool all round her, about four inches\
deep and reaching half down the hall.\
\
After a time she heard a little pattering of feet in the distance, and\
she hastily dried her eyes to see what was coming. It was the White\
Rabbit returning, splendidly dressed, with a pair of white kid gloves in\
one hand and a large fan in the other: he came trotting along in a great\
hurry, muttering to himself as he came, \'91Oh! the Duchess, the Duchess!\
Oh! won\'92t she be savage if I\'92ve kept her waiting!\'92 Alice felt so\
desperate that she was ready to ask help of any one; so, when the Rabbit\
came near her, she began, in a low, timid voice, \'91If you please, sir--\'92\
The Rabbit started violently, dropped the white kid gloves and the fan,\
and skurried away into the darkness as hard as he could go.\
\
Alice took up the fan and gloves, and, as the hall was very hot, she\
kept fanning herself all the time she went on talking: \'91Dear, dear! How\
queer everything is to-day! And yesterday things went on just as usual.\
I wonder if I\'92ve been changed in the night? Let me think: was I the\
same when I got up this morning? I almost think I can remember feeling a\
little different. But if I\'92m not the same, the next question is, Who\
in the world am I? Ah, THAT\'92S the great puzzle!\'92 And she began thinking\
over all the children she knew that were of the same age as herself, to\
see if she could have been changed for any of them.\
\
\'91I\'92m sure I\'92m not Ada,\'92 she said, \'91for her hair goes in such long\
ringlets, and mine doesn\'92t go in ringlets at all; and I\'92m sure I can\'92t\
be Mabel, for I know all sorts of things, and she, oh! she knows such a\
very little! Besides, SHE\'92S she, and I\'92m I, and--oh dear, how puzzling\
it all is! I\'92ll try if I know all the things I used to know. Let me\
see: four times five is twelve, and four times six is thirteen, and\
four times seven is--oh dear! I shall never get to twenty at that rate!\
However, the Multiplication Table doesn\'92t signify: let\'92s try Geography.\
London is the capital of Paris, and Paris is the capital of Rome, and\
Rome--no, THAT\'92S all wrong, I\'92m certain! I must have been changed for\
Mabel! I\'92ll try and say \'93How doth the little--\'93\'92 and she crossed her\
hands on her lap as if she were saying lessons, and began to repeat it,\
but her voice sounded hoarse and strange, and the words did not come the\
same as they used to do:--\
\
     \'91How doth the little crocodile\
      Improve his shining tail,\
     And pour the waters of the Nile\
      On every golden scale!\
\
     \'91How cheerfully he seems to grin,\
      How neatly spread his claws,\
     And welcome little fishes in\
      With gently smiling jaws!\'92\
\
\'91I\'92m sure those are not the right words,\'92 said poor Alice, and her eyes\
filled with tears again as she went on, \'91I must be Mabel after all, and\
I shall have to go and live in that poky little house, and have next to\
no toys to play with, and oh! ever so many lessons to learn! No, I\'92ve\
made up my mind about it; if I\'92m Mabel, I\'92ll stay down here! It\'92ll be no\
use their putting their heads down and saying \'93Come up again, dear!\'94 I\
shall only look up and say \'93Who am I then? Tell me that first, and then,\
if I like being that person, I\'92ll come up: if not, I\'92ll stay down here\
till I\'92m somebody else\'94--but, oh dear!\'92 cried Alice, with a sudden burst\
of tears, \'91I do wish they WOULD put their heads down! I am so VERY tired\
of being all alone here!\'92\
\
As she said this she looked down at her hands, and was surprised to see\
that she had put on one of the Rabbit\'92s little white kid gloves while\
she was talking. \'91How CAN I have done that?\'92 she thought. \'91I must\
be growing small again.\'92 She got up and went to the table to measure\
herself by it, and found that, as nearly as she could guess, she was now\
about two feet high, and was going on shrinking rapidly: she soon found\
out that the cause of this was the fan she was holding, and she dropped\
it hastily, just in time to avoid shrinking away altogether.\
\
\'91That WAS a narrow escape!\'92 said Alice, a good deal frightened at the\
sudden change, but very glad to find herself still in existence; \'91and\
now for the garden!\'92 and she ran with all speed back to the little door:\
but, alas! the little door was shut again, and the little golden key was\
lying on the glass table as before, \'91and things are worse than ever,\'92\
thought the poor child, \'91for I never was so small as this before, never!\
And I declare it\'92s too bad, that it is!\'92\
\
As she said these words her foot slipped, and in another moment, splash!\
she was up to her chin in salt water. Her first idea was that she\
had somehow fallen into the sea, \'91and in that case I can go back by\
railway,\'92 she said to herself. (Alice had been to the seaside once in\
her life, and had come to the general conclusion, that wherever you go\
to on the English coast you find a number of bathing machines in the\
sea, some children digging in the sand with wooden spades, then a row\
of lodging houses, and behind them a railway station.) However, she soon\
made out that she was in the pool of tears which she had wept when she\
was nine feet high.\
\
\'91I wish I hadn\'92t cried so much!\'92 said Alice, as she swam about, trying\
to find her way out. \'91I shall be punished for it now, I suppose, by\
being drowned in my own tears! That WILL be a queer thing, to be sure!\
However, everything is queer to-day.\'92\
\
Just then she heard something splashing about in the pool a little way\
off, and she swam nearer to make out what it was: at first she thought\
it must be a walrus or hippopotamus, but then she remembered how small\
she was now, and she soon made out that it was only a mouse that had\
slipped in like herself.\
\
\'91Would it be of any use, now,\'92 thought Alice, \'91to speak to this mouse?\
Everything is so out-of-the-way down here, that I should think very\
likely it can talk: at any rate, there\'92s no harm in trying.\'92 So she\
began: \'91O Mouse, do you know the way out of this pool? I am very tired\
of swimming about here, O Mouse!\'92 (Alice thought this must be the right\
way of speaking to a mouse: she had never done such a thing before, but\
she remembered having seen in her brother\'92s Latin Grammar, \'91A mouse--of\
a mouse--to a mouse--a mouse--O mouse!\'92) The Mouse looked at her rather\
inquisitively, and seemed to her to wink with one of its little eyes,\
but it said nothing.\
\
\'91Perhaps it doesn\'92t understand English,\'92 thought Alice; \'91I daresay it\'92s\
a French mouse, come over with William the Conqueror.\'92 (For, with all\
her knowledge of history, Alice had no very clear notion how long ago\
anything had happened.) So she began again: \'91Ou est ma chatte?\'92 which\
was the first sentence in her French lesson-book. The Mouse gave a\
sudden leap out of the water, and seemed to quiver all over with fright.\
\'91Oh, I beg your pardon!\'92 cried Alice hastily, afraid that she had hurt\
the poor animal\'92s feelings. \'91I quite forgot you didn\'92t like cats.\'92\
\
\'91Not like cats!\'92 cried the Mouse, in a shrill, passionate voice. \'91Would\
YOU like cats if you were me?\'92\
\
\'91Well, perhaps not,\'92 said Alice in a soothing tone: \'91don\'92t be angry\
about it. And yet I wish I could show you our cat Dinah: I think you\'92d\
take a fancy to cats if you could only see her. She is such a dear quiet\
thing,\'92 Alice went on, half to herself, as she swam lazily about in the\
pool, \'91and she sits purring so nicely by the fire, licking her paws and\
washing her face--and she is such a nice soft thing to nurse--and she\'92s\
such a capital one for catching mice--oh, I beg your pardon!\'92 cried\
Alice again, for this time the Mouse was bristling all over, and she\
felt certain it must be really offended. \'91We won\'92t talk about her any\
more if you\'92d rather not.\'92\
\
\'91We indeed!\'92 cried the Mouse, who was trembling down to the end of his\
tail. \'91As if I would talk on such a subject! Our family always HATED\
cats: nasty, low, vulgar things! Don\'92t let me hear the name again!\'92\
\
\'91I won\'92t indeed!\'92 said Alice, in a great hurry to change the subject of\
conversation. \'91Are you--are you fond--of--of dogs?\'92 The Mouse did not\
answer, so Alice went on eagerly: \'91There is such a nice little dog near\
our house I should like to show you! A little bright-eyed terrier, you\
know, with oh, such long curly brown hair! And it\'92ll fetch things when\
you throw them, and it\'92ll sit up and beg for its dinner, and all sorts\
of things--I can\'92t remember half of them--and it belongs to a farmer,\
you know, and he says it\'92s so useful, it\'92s worth a hundred pounds! He\
says it kills all the rats and--oh dear!\'92 cried Alice in a sorrowful\
tone, \'91I\'92m afraid I\'92ve offended it again!\'92 For the Mouse was swimming\
away from her as hard as it could go, and making quite a commotion in\
the pool as it went.\
\
So she called softly after it, \'91Mouse dear! Do come back again, and we\
won\'92t talk about cats or dogs either, if you don\'92t like them!\'92 When the\
Mouse heard this, it turned round and swam slowly back to her: its\
face was quite pale (with passion, Alice thought), and it said in a low\
trembling voice, \'91Let us get to the shore, and then I\'92ll tell you my\
history, and you\'92ll understand why it is I hate cats and dogs.\'92\
\
It was high time to go, for the pool was getting quite crowded with the\
birds and animals that had fallen into it: there were a Duck and a Dodo,\
a Lory and an Eaglet, and several other curious creatures. Alice led the\
way, and the whole party swam to the shore.\
\
\
