\
CHAPTER III. A Caucus-Race and a Long Tale\
\
They were indeed a queer-looking party that assembled on the bank--the\
birds with draggled feathers, the animals with their fur clinging close\
to them, and all dripping wet, cross, and uncomfortable.\
\
The first question of course was, how to get dry again: they had a\
consultation about this, and after a few minutes it seemed quite natural\
to Alice to find herself talking familiarly with them, as if she had\
known them all her life. Indeed, she had quite a long argument with the\
Lory, who at last turned sulky, and would only say, \'91I am older than\
you, and must know better\'92; and this Alice would not allow without\
knowing how old it was, and, as the Lory positively refused to tell its\
age, there was no more to be said.\
\
At last the Mouse, who seemed to be a person of authority among them,\
called out, \'91Sit down, all of you, and listen to me! I\'92LL soon make you\
dry enough!\'92 They all sat down at once, in a large ring, with the Mouse\
in the middle. Alice kept her eyes anxiously fixed on it, for she felt\
sure she would catch a bad cold if she did not get dry very soon.\
\
\'91Ahem!\'92 said the Mouse with an important air, \'91are you all ready? This\
is the driest thing I know. Silence all round, if you please! \'93William\
the Conqueror, whose cause was favoured by the pope, was soon submitted\
to by the English, who wanted leaders, and had been of late much\
accustomed to usurpation and conquest. Edwin and Morcar, the earls of\
Mercia and Northumbria--\'93\'92\
\
\'91Ugh!\'92 said the Lory, with a shiver.\
\
\'91I beg your pardon!\'92 said the Mouse, frowning, but very politely: \'91Did\
you speak?\'92\
\
\'91Not I!\'92 said the Lory hastily.\
\
\'91I thought you did,\'92 said the Mouse. \'91--I proceed. \'93Edwin and Morcar,\
the earls of Mercia and Northumbria, declared for him: and even Stigand,\
the patriotic archbishop of Canterbury, found it advisable--\'93\'92\
\
\'91Found WHAT?\'92 said the Duck.\
\
\'91Found IT,\'92 the Mouse replied rather crossly: \'91of course you know what\
\'93it\'94 means.\'92\
\
\'91I know what \'93it\'94 means well enough, when I find a thing,\'92 said the\
Duck: \'91it\'92s generally a frog or a worm. The question is, what did the\
archbishop find?\'92\
\
The Mouse did not notice this question, but hurriedly went on, \'91\'93--found\
it advisable to go with Edgar Atheling to meet William and offer him the\
crown. William\'92s conduct at first was moderate. But the insolence of his\
Normans--\'94 How are you getting on now, my dear?\'92 it continued, turning\
to Alice as it spoke.\
\
\'91As wet as ever,\'92 said Alice in a melancholy tone: \'91it doesn\'92t seem to\
dry me at all.\'92\
\
\'91In that case,\'92 said the Dodo solemnly, rising to its feet, \'91I move\
that the meeting adjourn, for the immediate adoption of more energetic\
remedies--\'92\
\
\'91Speak English!\'92 said the Eaglet. \'91I don\'92t know the meaning of half\
those long words, and, what\'92s more, I don\'92t believe you do either!\'92 And\
the Eaglet bent down its head to hide a smile: some of the other birds\
tittered audibly.\
\
\'91What I was going to say,\'92 said the Dodo in an offended tone, \'91was, that\
the best thing to get us dry would be a Caucus-race.\'92\
\
\'91What IS a Caucus-race?\'92 said Alice; not that she wanted much to know,\
but the Dodo had paused as if it thought that SOMEBODY ought to speak,\
and no one else seemed inclined to say anything.\
\
\'91Why,\'92 said the Dodo, \'91the best way to explain it is to do it.\'92 (And, as\
you might like to try the thing yourself, some winter day, I will tell\
you how the Dodo managed it.)\
\
First it marked out a race-course, in a sort of circle, [\'91the exact\
shape doesn\'92t matter,\'92 it said,) and then all the party were placed\
along the course, here and there. There was no \'91One, two, three, and\
away,\'92 but they began running when they liked, and left off when they\
liked, so that it was not easy to know when the race was over. However,\
when they had been running half an hour or so, and were quite dry again,\
the Dodo suddenly called out \'91The race is over!\'92 and they all crowded\
round it, panting, and asking, \'91But who has won?\'92\
\
This question the Dodo could not answer without a great deal of thought,\
and it sat for a long time with one finger pressed upon its forehead\
(the position in which you usually see Shakespeare, in the pictures\
of him), while the rest waited in silence. At last the Dodo said,\
\'91EVERYBODY has won, and all must have prizes.\'92\
\
\'91But who is to give the prizes?\'92 quite a chorus of voices asked.\
\
\'91Why, SHE, of course,\'92 said the Dodo, pointing to Alice with one finger;\
and the whole party at once crowded round her, calling out in a confused\
way, \'91Prizes! Prizes!\'92\
\
Alice had no idea what to do, and in despair she put her hand in her\
pocket, and pulled out a box of comfits, (luckily the salt water had\
not got into it), and handed them round as prizes. There was exactly one\
a-piece all round.\
\
\'91But she must have a prize herself, you know,\'92 said the Mouse.\
\
\'91Of course,\'92 the Dodo replied very gravely. \'91What else have you got in\
your pocket?\'92 he went on, turning to Alice.\
\
\'91Only a thimble,\'92 said Alice sadly.\
\
\'91Hand it over here,\'92 said the Dodo.\
\
Then they all crowded round her once more, while the Dodo solemnly\
presented the thimble, saying \'91We beg your acceptance of this elegant\
thimble\'92; and, when it had finished this short speech, they all cheered.\
\
Alice thought the whole thing very absurd, but they all looked so grave\
that she did not dare to laugh; and, as she could not think of anything\
to say, she simply bowed, and took the thimble, looking as solemn as she\
could.\
\
The next thing was to eat the comfits: this caused some noise and\
confusion, as the large birds complained that they could not taste\
theirs, and the small ones choked and had to be patted on the back.\
However, it was over at last, and they sat down again in a ring, and\
begged the Mouse to tell them something more.\
\
\'91You promised to tell me your history, you know,\'92 said Alice, \'91and why\
it is you hate--C and D,\'92 she added in a whisper, half afraid that it\
would be offended again.\
\
\'91Mine is a long and a sad tale!\'92 said the Mouse, turning to Alice, and\
sighing.\
\
\'91It IS a long tail, certainly,\'92 said Alice, looking down with wonder at\
the Mouse\'92s tail; \'91but why do you call it sad?\'92 And she kept on puzzling\
about it while the Mouse was speaking, so that her idea of the tale was\
something like this:--\
